Ya but, have you encountered WGA(Window Genuine Advantage) yet? The reason I
bring that up is, I have a 250gb drive that was cloned from a 80gb drive.
Since that cloning I accidentally got suckered into installing WGA. This
allowed me to download the latest patches for Winxp, but little did I know
that with WGA installed, everytime you boot up it contacts MS server to
check for authenticity of the operating system. Not a problem until you
decide to replace the original drive with the clone. From what I have heard
on some forums is that the MS authenticity server gathers up info and checks
it against their database. Some of this info is your hard drive serial
number, your bios checksum, and various other sundry  bits.
So when I put the 250gb in service and booted up, waahla there was a message
telling me that my hardware configuration had changed significantly and I
had to go through a revalidation process. I wasn't in the mood for that and
just put the original drive back in service. Since then I have been
gathering info on this WGA and it's genesis, trying to understand the
ramifications concerning cloning. As it's implemented right now, It appears,
that if I clone to a larger drive, I might not be able to pass the
validation process and will have to fork over $99 to MS to use the same
operating system that I originally  paid $99 for on the larger drive. I
think that I'm being taken advantage of, but I also believe that under the
terms of their EULA they are in the right. I have since learned there are at
least two class action suits and will watch them, but in the mean time will
explore Linux.

--
