This information about Windows Genuine Advantage is sort of right.  At
the time I ran into the problem, MS reported that a score is calculated
based on the hardware.  If you change out a hard drive, you add to that
score.  If you change out a DVD player, HD, floppy and video card, you
will have a higher score.  At some point MS will decide the computer the
operating system (OS) is registered in is different than the one it
is in.  This is done during updating, not during booting.

At the time, I had a number of identical laptops.  One computer failed
and I wanted to place the drive from that computer in another.  The
failed computer was to go to warranty repair.  MS reported the OS was
invalid.  I called MS, explained, read off the stickers on both
machines, was given a new validation number and off I went.

Of the methods to protect their rights to their operating system, this
method was inconvenient but not insurmountable.

I recently moved another drive into a like computer and found MS didn't
complain.  Perhaps something changed.  Perhaps it was because the two
drives were the same model.

